# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1915-buffalo-blues-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1915-buffalo-blues-season/1914-buffalo-buffeds-season] The **1914 Buffalo Buffeds season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1915-buffalo-blues-season/1914-buffalo-buffeds-season] The Buffeds finished 80–71, good for 4th place in the Federal League, 7 games behind the Indianapolis Hoosiers.
[src:1915-buffalo-blues-season/1915-baltimore-terrapins-season] The **1915 Baltimore Terrapins season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1915-buffalo-blues-season/1915-baltimore-terrapins-season] The Terrapins finished in 8th place in the Federal League, 40 games behind the Chicago Whales.
[src:1915-buffalo-blues-season/1915-baltimore-terrapins-season] After the season, both the team and the league folded.
[src:1915-buffalo-blues-season/1915-boston-braves-season] The **1915 Boston Braves season** was the 45th season of the franchise.
[src:1915-buffalo-blues-season/1915-boston-braves-season] The Braves finished second in the National League with a record of 83 wins and 69 losses, seven games behind the National League champion Philadelphia Phillies.
[src:1915-buffalo-blues-season/1915-boston-braves-season] The 1915 season was notable for the opening of Braves Field on August 13, the last of the National League's "jewel box" stadiums to be built.
[src:1915-buffalo-blues-season/1915-boston-braves-season] In the final game of the season, a 15–8 loss to the New York Giants, Joe Shannon made his final Major League appearance, and Red Shannon made his first Major League appearance.
[src:1915-buffalo-blues-season/1915-boston-braves-season] The two were twins, marking the first of three times that twins played on the same team (along with Eddie and Johnny O'Brien and Jose and Ozzie Canseco).
[src:1915-buffalo-blues-season/1915-boston-red-sox-season] The **1915 Boston Red Sox season** was the 15th season in the franchise's Major League Baseball history.
[src:1915-buffalo-blues-season/1915-boston-red-sox-season] The Red Sox finished first in the American League (AL) with a record of 101 wins and 50 losses.
[src:1915-buffalo-blues-season/1915-boston-red-sox-season] The team then faced the National League (NL) champion Philadelphia Phillies in the 1915 World Series, which the Red Sox won in five games to capture the franchise's third World Series.
[src:1915-buffalo-blues-season/1915-boston-red-sox-season] While the Red Sox' home field was Fenway Park, their two home games of the World Series were played at Braves Field, due to its larger seating capacity.
[src:1915-buffalo-blues-season/1915-brooklyn-robins-season] The **1915 Brooklyn Robins season** improved enough to finish in third place, just 10 games behind the National League champion Philadelphia Phillies.
[src:1915-buffalo-blues-season/1915-brooklyn-robins-season] It was the teams first winning season since 1903 when they were still known as the Superbas.
[src:1915-buffalo-blues-season/1915-brooklyn-tip-tops-season] The **1915 Brooklyn Tip-Tops season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1915-buffalo-blues-season/1915-brooklyn-tip-tops-season] The Tip-Tops finished in 7th place in the Federal League, 16 games behind the Chicago Whales.
[src:1915-buffalo-blues-season/1915-brooklyn-tip-tops-season] The season was notable in that it featured one of the only known major-league professional baseball games of the modern era in which admission was free (June 28, 1914, vs. the Chicago Whales).
[src:1915-buffalo-blues-season/1915-buffalo-blues-season] The **1915 Buffalo Blues season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1915-buffalo-blues-season/1915-buffalo-blues-season] The team, which did not have an official nickname but was generally known as the **Buffeds** the previous year, adopted the "Blues" nickname for the 1915 season.
[src:1915-buffalo-blues-season/1915-buffalo-blues-season] They were also known as the **Buffalo Federals** or **Buffalo Feds**.
[src:1915-buffalo-blues-season/1915-buffalo-blues-season] They finished 74–78, good for 6th place in the Federal League, 12 games behind the Chicago Whales.
[src:1915-buffalo-blues-season/1915-buffalo-blues-season] It would be 105 more years—when the Toronto Blue Jays temporarily moved to Buffalo to play the pandemic-shortened 2020 season and avoid border restrictions—before Buffalo hosted Major League Baseball again.
[src:1915-buffalo-blues-season/1915-chicago-cubs-season] The **1915 Chicago Cubs season** was the 44th season of the Chicago Cubs franchise, the 40th in the National League and the 23rd and final at West Side Park.
[src:1915-buffalo-blues-season/1915-chicago-cubs-season] The Cubs finished fourth in the National League with a record of 73–80.
